    "source_sections": {
      "references": "",
      "remarks": "A question of Erd\\H{o}s, Eggleton, and Selfridge, who write that 'plausible conjectures on primes' imply that $F(n)\\leq n$ for only finitely many $n$, and in fact it is possible that this quantity is always at least $n+(1-o(1))\\sqrt{n}$ (note that it is trivially $\\leq n+\\sqrt{n}$).\n\nTao has discussed this problem in a blog post.\n\nSarosh Adenwalla has observed that the first question is equivalent to [430]. Indeed, if $n$ is large and $a_i$ is the sequence defined in the latter problem, then [430] implies that there is a composite $a_j$ such that $a_j-p(a_j)>n$ and hence $F(n)>n$.\n\nSee also [463]."
    },
    "source_state": "open",
    "tags": [
      "number theory"
    ]
  },
